# specific time periods.

# We want the full crime acitvity for full years. 2017 is not enough over yet. 
# In order to get accurate results as possible. 
df = df[df.Year != 2017]
df['Reported_Date'] = df['Reported_Date'].str.split(' ').str[0]
df.loc[df['Time_of_Day'] == 'MIDNIGHT', 'Time_of_Day'] = 2
df.loc[df['Time_of_Day'] == 'EVENING', 'Time_of_Day'] = 1
df.loc[df['Time_of_Day'] == 'DAY', 'Time_of_Day'] = 0
df.loc[df['Crime_Type'] == 'Violent', 'Crime_Type'] = 1
df.loc[df['Crime_Type'] == 'Non-Violent', 'Crime_Type'] = 0

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Exploratory data analysis (EDA) is the next important step in the field of data science. The purpose of this step is to help data scientist see patterns and trends in data sets. To begin exploratory analysis, it is often done through visual/graphical methods which has an array of different techinques. These graphical techinques include using scatter plots, box plots, multi-vari charts, histograms and other more visual involved techinques like maps.

Moreover, EDA helps to find insight on data that were not clearly seen or not worth doing further analysis with the data set. Specifically, this entails looking at correlation between variables in how they interact with each other over a period of time, how they increase in value, and etc. EDA is about gaining knowledge about our dataset and having a better undederstanding in how these variables correlate or dont correlte with each other. Ultimately, to make predictions and to test hypothesis, which will be discussed in the later part of this tutorial.

3.1 Average Crime Acts Per The Hour¶

One of the variables that we can start to analysis, is in regards to the time series of the criminal acts throughout a 24 hour period. Looking through the data frame we can use the groupby function from pandas to group the years to get the total number of days with X number of years in this case its 8 years. Following up, we then groupby the main dataframe by hour to aggregate the sum of all criminal acts for each hour and then divide by the total number of days to obtain the average number of crimes.

In [6]:
# Obtain the number of years in the data frame
num_years = len(df.groupby(['Year']))
# Multiply that to get the number of days for x number of years.
number_of_days = num_years* 365

# To aggregate the number of criminal acts for each hour of the 8 year period.
hour_df = df.groupby(['Hour']).agg({'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()
hour_df['Avg_Crim_Ct_Hr'] = hour_df['Criminal_Count']/number_of_days
hour_df.head()

3.2 Seasonal Crime Rates¶

The next thing one might try to analyze in regards to time, is if there is a trend between the the crime activity and time of the year. In this respect, we can can analysis the seasons of the year to see if there is relationship between crime rates for winter season, spring season and etc.

In [8]:
# Following the Northern Meteorological Seasons
# Fall September - November
# Winter December - February
# Spring March - May
# Summer June - August
# Drag contents following the condition statements into their respected seasons data frames.
fall_crime_df = df[(df.Month >= 9) & (df.Month <= 11)]
spring_crime_df = df[(df.Month >= 3) & (df.Month <= 5)]
winter_crime_df = df[(df.Month >= 12) | ((df.Month >= 1)& (df.Month <= 2))]
summer_crime_df = df[(df.Month >= 6) & (df.Month <= 8)]

# Aggregate the total crime acts each day for all 4 seasons between the year 2008 to 2016
fall_crime_dfs = fall_crime_df.groupby(['Month','Day']).agg({\
                                                    'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()

spring_crime_dfs = spring_crime_df.groupby(['Month','Day']).agg({\
                                                    'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()

winter_crime_dfs = winter_crime_df.groupby(['Month','Day']).agg({\
                                                    'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()

summer_crime_dfs = summer_crime_df.groupby(['Month','Day']).agg({\
                                                    'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()
# Reconfiguring the shape of the line plot.
fig_size = plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"]
fig_size[0] = 15
fig_size[1] = 9
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = fig_size

# Plot each individual season wich represented by each line graph shown below.
plt.plot(fall_crime_dfs.index ,fall_crime_dfs['Criminal_Count'], label = 'Fall') 
plt.plot(spring_crime_dfs.index, spring_crime_dfs['Criminal_Count'], label = 'Spring') 
plt.plot(winter_crime_dfs.index, winter_crime_dfs['Criminal_Count'], label = 'Winter') 
plt.plot(summer_crime_dfs.index, summer_crime_dfs['Criminal_Count'], label = 'Summer') 

# Labeling the graph.
plt.title('Seasonal Total Criminal Activity (2008 - 2016)')
plt.ylabel('Criminal Activity')
plt.xlabel('90 Day Time Period Per Season')
plt.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.1, 1.0))
plt.show()

Observing the graph one can see that for the first two months of each season, crimes rates for spring and winter season tend be a lot lower in comparison to fall and summer. But as you look up closely, towards the end of the seasons the crime rates starts to merge, and have similar criem activity, with spring slowly creeping up into the summer season which may indicate that crimes occur because of not so extreme temperatures of the year. In addition, towards the end of fall, crime rates start to decrease, creeping into the winter season.

3.4 Crime Charge Popularity Chart¶

Previously, it was noted that there was a big change from the year 2009 to 2014. Although we can't completely narrow down an exact reason for this trend, one of features we can look at in order to try and understand this trend is to analysis the crime offense charges. By grabbing the contents of the main DC crime dataframe for the lowest point 2009-2019 and 2014-2015, we can aggregate the total amount of charges for each crime offense. Which include arson, theft homicide, burglary, assault and other offenses. After aggregating the data, we can then use matplotlib bar functions to plot and measure all the crime offense charge to see the changes between the two groups. And hopefully getting a better understanding.

In [10]:
# Split the main data frame into two different data frames one for the year 09-10 and 14-15. 
df_09_10 = df[(df.Year == 2009) | (df.Year == 2010)]
df_14_15 = df[(df.Year == 2014) | (df.Year == 2015)]

# Sum up total offensive charges for the two groups. 
charge_10 = df_09_10.groupby('Offense_Charge').agg({'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()
charge_15 = df_14_15.groupby('Offense_Charge').agg({'Criminal_Count': 'sum'}).reset_index()

# Configure size of graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(23,15))

            width = 0.25, label = '2009 - 2010')
plt.bar([0.25,1.25,2.25,3.25,4.25,5.25,6.25,7.25,8.25], charge_15['Criminal_Count'], \
            color = '#F78F1E', width = 0.25, label = '2014 - 2015')
ax.set_xticks([0.1,1.1,2.1,3.1,4.1,5.1,6.1,7.1,8.1])
ax.set_xticklabels(charge_10['Offense_Charge'])

# Changing the label size and rearranging the label box.
ax.set_ylabel('Criminal Activity Count', size = 18)
ax.set_xlabel('Types of Criminal Charge', size = 18)
ax.set_title('Criminal Charge Popularity Ranking', size = 23)
plt.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.10, 1.0))
plt.show()

One of the most noticeable results of the graph, is the huge increase for theft charges, which has the greatest increase rate out of the 7 other offense charges. In addition, charges like burglary, motor theft, and robbery charges slightly dropped. And maybe because of the growth in technological advances, tools to get into cars or increase in the number of people owning cars could maybe explain this change.

3.7 Offense Charges Distribution In DC¶

One can also look into the offense charges in the data set. By using one of python's packages, folium, one can plot markers for some of the crime data. Taking .004 of the 300,000+ data we can achieve a general pattern of which quandrant has an odd distribution of specific offense charges..

In [13]:
# Zoom into DC coordinates
map_osm = folium.Map(location=[38.913632846803, -77.0702085907701], zoom_start=11)
# Sample DC data frame
sample_crime_df = df.sample(frac = .004, replace= False).reset_index(drop=True)
# Set up Market Clusters
marker_cluster = MarkerCluster().add_to(map_osm)

# Iterrate through dataframe plotting crime acts.
for index,row in sample_crime_df.iterrows():
    lat = row['Latitude']
    long = row['Longitude']
    if row['Offense_Charge'] == 'ARSON':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='white')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'ASSAULT W/DANGEROUS WEAPON':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='black')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'BURGLARY':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='blue')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'HOMICIDE':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='green')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'MOTOR VEHICLE THEFT':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='red')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'ROBBERY':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='purple')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'SEX ABUSE':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='grey')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    elif row['Offense_Charge'] == 'THEFT F/AUTO':
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='yellow')).add_to(marker_cluster)
    else:
        folium.Marker([long,lat], icon=folium.Icon(color='pink')).add_to(marker_cluster)
map_osm

4. Machine Learning & Hypothesis Testing¶

After completing the exploratory analysis step and now having a better understanding about our data set, the next important step is to utilize machine learning techniques. Essentially, the purpose of machine learning is to make predictions on the data set. And this depends on which kind of machine learning algorithmn one uses which can be commonly categoried into the 3 areas, supervised, unsupervised, and reinforced learning.

With this in mind, I will be using the random forest classifier which follows under the supervised learning category. Using this technique one will train the algorithm to learn data set in order to create a model to make predictions. Specifically, we will look at the "time of day" variables which consist of evening, midnight, and day and "crime type" variables, violent and non - violent crimes, to see if there is a relationship to make predictions on. In addition, for more information on machine learning algorithmns, check out: https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2017/09/common-machine-learning-algorithms/

4.1 Sample and Split Data¶

Now that we've'some of the patterns we can test data and make predictions. First step is to shuffle the row values in the data frame. After,we can split dataframe data into a training data set and testing dataset. One to teach and train the aglorithmn with, the training, and one to later test the predictions results with the, the testing data set.

In [14]:
# Shuffle data frame rows
shuffled_df = df.sample(frac=1)
# Split data into training and testing sets.
split_data = np.random.rand(len(shuffled_df)) < 0.7
training_set = shuffled_df[split_data]
testing_set = shuffled_df[~split_data]

4.2 Set Training and Testing Data Into X and Y Values¶

Now we can asign time of day values to the x and y training data and crime type values to the x and y testing data. One thingto keep in mind, we only work with the training data for now, and we dont touch the testing data yet.

In [15]:
# Split the columns into x and y training and testing data.
x_train_val = training_set[['Time_of_Day']].values
y_train_val = training_set.Crime_Type.values
x_test_val = testing_set[['Time_of_Day']].values
y_test_val = testing_set.Crime_Type.values

# Convert data type into integer
x_train_val=x_train_val.astype('int')
y_train_val=y_train_val.astype('int')

4.3 Random Forest Classifier¶

After we obtain the x and y training sets, we will train the algorithmn, Random Forest Classifier to fit a model from the training data to make predictions. For more in depth information about Random Forest Classifier, visit: https://medium.com/machine-learning-101/chapter-5-random-forest-classifier-56dc7425c3e1

In [16]:
# Create a randome forest object, then use the fit function to come up with a model based 
# on the x and y training data.
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=10)
clf.fit(x_train_val, y_train_val)

# Use predict functions to make the predictions for the y values based on the testing values.
pred_outcome_y = clf.predict(x_test_val)
pred_outcome_y = pred_outcome_y.astype('int')
testing_set['Crime_Type'] = testing_set['Crime_Type'].astype('int')

# Finally, we match the accuracy of the results between the y testing values and y predicted value from the
# random forest algorithmn. 
print("Accuracy for Random Forest Classifier:")
print(accuracy_score(testing_set['Crime_Type'],pred_outcome_y))

Accuracy for Random Forest Classifier:
0.813463536697

Insight & Policy Decision¶

Finally, after doing all of this analysis, and testing, we can now make the decision. But prior to this, one should ask themselves, how good does the hypothesis hold up? Do we accept the null hypothesis? Which implies that there is no relationship between the time of day and violent and non violent crimes. Well, looking at the data above, we test the accuracy of the score using accuracy score function from scikit-learn. And for more information on scikit-learn, check out documentation: http://scikit-learn.org/stable/. The results of the accuracy score show a value of roughly 81 percent, which is relatively high. Thus, we can conclude that there is strong correlation between time of day and crime type. As a result, we can reject the null hypothesis

Conclusion¶

To wrap things up, some key points to remember about this whole process is that its important to not skip any of these steps in this whoe process. Every key component of each step helps us build a more solid and accurate results. We saw that that data processing/preparation is important in cleaning up the data to be use for analysis. And then using analysis to find trends and patterns on the data set. In addition, looking back, one can see that there are many routes one can take to analysis which variables to match against. Furthermore, we could have gone deeper into the map visualization, and look which neighborhoods has the most crimes, or which crime offences are most frequent at the night. With that being said, there numerous ways to approach this step. Moving over to the next, machine learning and hypothesis testing are both important steps because its essential the whole purpose of the tutorial and for data scientist in general to carry out. We use these tools to solve problems in this world by making predictions to improve situations.
